lace, but the modern surname in Britain is associated mainly with Devon, where the earliest record of the surname is found in 1761, and is probably a substitution for   Elford  , an earlier form of the Devon placename. The Devon place, a hamlet in Buckland Monachorum, is not officially on record as <i>Yelverton</i> until the 19th century, when the Great Western Railway so named the station it built there in 1859. It is a dialect pronunciation of <i>Elverton</i>, which is first recorded in 1765 as an extended form of its medieval name <i>Elford</i> + <i>-ton</i> ‘town’. The Norfolk placename is recorded as <i>Ailuertuna</i> in 1086, and probably derives from the Old English personal name <i>Æthelfrith</i> or <i>Geldfrith</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."],"variants":[{"name":"Elford","meanings":["English: habitational name from Yelverton in Buckland Monachorum (Devon), recorded as <i>Elleford</i> in 1291 (see   Yelverton  ), named from the Old English personal name <i>Ella</i> or <i>elle</i>, <i>ellen</i> ‘elder tree’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’. The name may also derive from any of the places called Elford in Staffordshire and Northumberland, both probably from the Old English personal name <i>Ella</i> + <i>ford</i>."]},{"name":"Yelvington","meanings":["Probably an altered form of English   Yelverton  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Yelverton was born in 1281, in Rackheath, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, John YELVERTON Sir, was 25 and his mother, Elizabeth Reade, was 22. He married Maud Chappis in 1301, in Rackheath, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1307, in his hometown, at the age of 26."},"et":{"1281–1307":"1281–1307","1283–1307":"1283–1307","1300–1383":"1300–1383","1256–1307":"1256–1307","1260–1307":"1260–1307","1301":"1301","1256":"1256","1300":"1300","ABT 1300":"umbes 1300","1383":"1383","1283":"1283","1260":"1260","1281":"1281","1307":"1307","ABT 1307":"umbes 1307","ABT 1280":"umbes 1280","Rackheath, Norfolk County, England":"Rackheath, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Rackheath, Norfolk, England":"Rackheath, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1281–1307":"1281–1307","1283–1307":"1283–1307","1300–1383":"1300–1383","1256–1307":"1256–1307","1260–1307":"1260–1307","1301":"1301","1256":"1256","1300":"1300","ABT 1300":"noin 1300","1383":"1383","1283":"1283","1260":"1260","1281":"1281","1307":"1307","ABT 1307":"noin 1307","ABT 1280":"noin 1280","Rackheath, Norfolk County, England":"Rackheath, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Rackheath, Norfolk, England":"Rackheath, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1281–1307":"1281–1307","1283–1307":"1283–1307","1300–1383":"1300–1383","1256–1307":"1256–1307","1260–1307":"1260–1307","1301":"1301","1256":"1256","1300":"1300","ABT 1300":"environ 1300","1383":"1383","1283":"1283","1260":"1260","1281":"1281","1307":"1307","ABT 1307":"environ 1307","ABT 1280":"environ 1280","Rackheath, Norfolk County, England":"Rackheath, Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Rackheath, Norfolk, England":"Rackheath, Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Thomas Yelverton est né en 1281, à Rackheath, Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, John YELVERTON Sir, avait 25 ans et sa mère, Elizabeth Reade, avait 22 ans. Il a épousé Maud Chappis en 1301, à Rackheath, Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Il est décédé en 1307, dans sa ville natale